	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Sat Mar 07, 2015 6:52 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: How to start? What to use?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I try to keep everything as simple as possible, so I avoid at all costs anything that needs to be installed and/or configured before it can be used. Not only to avoid the inevitable frustration, but also so that I can easily download my project files and work on different machines, even ones that don't belong to me.<br /><br />That being said, I'm a fan of no-frills assemblers, that are able to take nothing but an ASM file (not that I use a single ASM file, I make heavy use of includes, bit that's beside the point) and spit out a finished ROM file. None need for config files, linking things, or any of that. Honestly, I'd code directly in hex if I didn't need the convenience of labels and assembly-time math, but anything more than that is overkill to me.<br /><br />The two assemblers commonly used by NES programmers that fall in that category are NESASM and ASM6. NESASM uses non-standard 6502 syntax for some commands, forces you to do a few things that aren't necessarily relevant on the NES (like starting a new bank every 8KB) and has a buggy history (it used to produce corrupt binaries instead of reporting assembly errors, driving programmers crazy - apparently this aspect improved a lot in newer versions), so I'm with ASM6, which is much more versatile, but just as easy to use.<br /><br />I posted some <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?f=10&amp;t=6160" class="postlink">ASM6 templates</a> for the most popular mappers among homebrew programmers a few years ago if you're interested. Just call ASM6 with the ASM file as a parameter and you should get a working NES file, you don't need anything else.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


